ce:section.ce:para:
The nanobiosensor was analytically characterized by detecting a buffered solution spiked with different concentrations of the commercial spike protein and measuring the resultant drop in the current by DPV (see Fig. 2
                     ). For the current value, a baseline was initially drawn on each of the DPV measurement curves, from which the peak height was obtained, and then the current delta of this peak height was calculated concerning the BSA surface blocking curve to obtain the calibration curve. The response was spike protein concentration-dependent in a linear range between 0 and 1.5 µg/mL and a sensitivity of 13.2 µA*mL/µg. The limit of detection (LOD) was estimated to be 60.14 ng/mL or 0.78 nM based on the 3-sigma criteria from equation S1. The as-developed format takes advantage of the electrochemical properties of electrodeposited GQDs@AuPt to detect clinically relevant concentrations of the spike protein. It is known that the viral loading in samples from infected patients is between 104 and 1012 copies/mL [36,37,38], with an average loading of 9.9x108 copies/mL. Considering that each viral copy contains an average of 100 copies of spike protein [37] and that the molecular weight of this protein is 180–200 kDa [39], it was calculated an approximate concentration ranging from 0.3 pg/mL to 3 µg/mL of spike protein in positive samples in which the biosensor presented its linear range. The LOD is comparable with other electrochemical biosensors reported in the literature for SARS-CoV-2 spike protein detection. For example, an electrochemical biosensor based on graphene electrodes functionalized with a 1-pyrene butyric acid N-hydroxysuccinimide ester (PBASE) linker achieved a LOD of 260 nM by square wave voltammetry [40]. And a biosensor based on TiO2 nanotubes achieved a LOD of 0.7 nM by chronoamperometry [41]. Similarly, a biosensor based on carbon cloth-AuNPs detected the spike protein, achieving a 37.8 ng/mL LOD by chronopotentiometry [42]. Table 1
                      summarizes some of the latest published work on electrochemical immunosensors for spike protein detection.
